 WSJ880617-0024 White House Moves to Deal With Drought --- Farm Export Subsidy Curbs Are Mulled; Stock Prices Drop on Inflation Fears --- This article was prepared by Bruce Ingersoll in Washington And Scott Kilman and Alex Kotlowitz in Chicago CMD MON FAR REL BNK ECO EXE AGD WASHINGTON The Reagan administration moved to deal with the worsening drought, and a top trade official said that farm export subsidies may have to be curbed.
 President Reagan appointed an interagency group to deal with the drought and Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng authorized farmers in drought parched counties in 13 states to harvest hay on idled crop land in the government's Conservation Reserve Program.
